tr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FG021759%2F1"><gtr:id>884CC0CE-00F1-40E1-99AC-89D4BD2D07F8</gtr:id><gtr:title>Awareness of number marking during reading and spelling</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/G021759/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>At 16, the average deaf school leaver has a reading-age equivalent to a 9-year-old hearing child, impacting on employment and recreational opportunities. Hearing children rely heavily on speech while reading ? using letter-to-sound rules to translate unknown written words. Deaf children typically find letter-to-sound conversion arduous and also often have limited speech vocabulary. Therefore, alternative decoding methods are required to improve literacy. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>The present research examines deaf children's knowledge of morphology. Morphologically related words often share spellings. For example, plural nouns are usually formed by adding &amp;quot;s&amp;quot; to the singular, even though pronunciation varies (compare the &amp;quot;s&amp;quot; in &amp;quot;dogs&amp;quot;, &amp;quot;cats&amp;quot;, and &amp;quot;horses&amp;quot;). These grammatical spelling rules must be learned, yet little research has examined this component of literacy acquisition. A series of empirical articles will demonstrate that deaf children have an awareness of the morphological relationships and generalise morphological spelling rules (eg dog-dogs). However, deaf children appear to be particularly poor at learning exceptions to rules (eg foot-feet), process grammar slowly and fail to make explicit use of this information.&lt;/p>

&lt;p>In addition to producing a series of empirical articles, a pilot study examining the eye movements during reading will enable the continuation of this research on completion of the fellowship.&lt;br />&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2012-02-29</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2010-03-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>78669</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>560DC269-4E02-4F3F-9BBD-0D0808982F74</gtr:id><gtr:title>Agreeing to disagree: deaf and hearing children's awareness of subject-verb number agreement.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Quarterly journal of experimental psychology (2006)</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/9dcaa04ca56850b3ec64938d4bbba73a"><gtr:id>9dcaa04ca56850b3ec64938d4bbba73a</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Breadmore HL</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2014-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:issn>1747-0218</gtr:issn><gtr:outcomeId>54298861abd394.42552209</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>52C5D9EF-0F2C-4D7D-BBFC-D24883C6D5DD</gtr:id><gtr:title>Deaf and hearing children's plural noun spelling.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Quarterly journal of experimental psychology (2006)</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/9dcaa04ca56850b3e